From Mike Lipsie MPU Subject Re Permanent Swap File In article Martin Linsenbigler writes When I first setup windows using the self load mode It grabbed about megs of swap file space my meg HD was nearly empty at that I deleted windows for a time and recently reloaded now my HD is nearly full and windows just took One of the rules for a permanent swap file is that it must be contiguous non fragmented I suspect that is more responsible for the difference than the amount of free disk in your I have read somewhere that the best rule of thumb is have your permanent swap file the same size as your regular RAM I have megs of RAM and windows took meg perm swap Works very In fact with my available HD space about megs it won't let me make the swap file any You should change your virtual mem swap file to megs I think that is what you said your RAM It depends on what you are We had to increase our swap file I think it is now when some applications couldn't run without everything else Mike Lipsie work Mitsubishi Electronic Research Laboratory home mikel